@Kogo - since you commented about an update on my previous forecast After Washington beat Dallas and some of their competitor games have played out, I'm adjusting the individual probabilities I've ascribed for each game: Pitt & Seattle: Unchanged, still very unlikely
SF: increase to 35% (up from 30%)
Carolina & Philly: significant increase to 40% (up from 30%) The biggest impact, of course, is that now the probability of Washington having beat Dallas is 100% - giving them one of the two wins necessary and massively jumping the probability of yes to 78%. Since a game was won and progress was made towards "yes" I'll be updating the probability all the way to 78 rather than adjusting from the 55% prior.

Updating my forecast following their win over the cowboys. Now they just need to win at least one game of their final five.  There have been 177 teams that have started a season 4-7. Of those, 170 ended up with at least 5 wins. This gives them a 97% chance of winning at least 5 games.  Looking at their remaining matchups and using 538s probabilities of them winning, their probability of winning at least one is: 1 - P(lose all of them) = 
1 - [(1.00-0.14) * (1.00-0.31) * (1.00-0.31) * (1.00-0.47) * (1.00-0.43)] = 1-12 = 88%. 
@PIT 14%
@SF 31%
vs SEA 31%
vs CAR 47%
@PHI 43% I'll split the difference and give them a 90% chance of winning at least 5 games.

Updating my prediction through 10 games. Baserate: WFT has now won 3 games and lost 7. Of the teams 143 teams that started 3-7, 105 won at least 5 games. That suggests a 73% chance.  Inside angle: I like how @ray-wallin went about that, so I update it for the remaining 6 games. I use 538's predictions instead [1] @DAL  52% 
@PIT 14%
@SF 31% 
vs SEA 31%
vs CAR 47% 
@PHI 43% This suggests around 2.5-3 more wins this season. As a result, I'm raising my prediction to 65%.  [1] https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-nfl-predictions/games/

At the midpoint of the season WFT is 2-6. Remaining Schedule with early or projected lines:
@DET (3-5) +4.5
vs CIN (2-5-1) -1.5
@DAL (2-7) +8
@PIT (8-0) +8.5
@SF (4-5) +7
vs SEA (6-2) +5
vs CAR (3-6) +1
@PHI (3-4-1) +5 Based on the probabilities associated with the spreads, WFT should win 2.63 games the rest of the season.  CIN and CAR are the two most likely wins (still close to a 50/50 proposition). WFT has about a 32% chance of beating DET, SEA, and PHI. They have a 24% chance of beating SF, and about a 20% chance of beating DAL and PIT. WFT beat both DAL and PHI this season at home, which is not likely to repeat while they are on the road. WFT's overall schedule strength to date is lower than every one of their remaining opponents with the exception of the undefeated Steelers.  Realistically I see them pulling of 2 more wins this season, but wouldn't be surprised if that was 3 wins or 4 wins depending on how many of the opponents players end up on IR or out for COVID.
